        <title>Sedimentation plates</title>
        <image align="center" candidates="{'*': 'Sedimentation\\Images/sed_plates.png'}" uri="Sedimentation\Images/sed_plates.png" width="250px"></image>
        <paragraph>Plate modules are mounted on top of the sedimentation tanks to reduce the size of the smallest particles that can be captured. They increase the surface area where particles can stick and be captured. That is, the plates reduce the distance a particle suspended between them has to fall down before it can stick to a solid surface (<number_reference internal="True" refid="figure-diff-diagram" title="Fig. %s"><inline classes="std std-numref">Fig. 35</inline></number_reference>).</paragraph>
        <target refid="figure-diff-diagram"></target>
        <figure align="center" ids="id1 figure-diff-diagram" names="figure_diff_diagram">
            <image candidates="{'*': 'Sedimentation\\Images/diff_diagram.png'}" uri="Sedimentation\Images/diff_diagram.png" width="750px"></image>
            <caption>The sedimentation plates reduce the fall of the floc to a solid surface. In the diagrams you can see the difference between the distance a particle has to fall in the same period of time with plates and without plates.</caption>
        </figure>
        <paragraph>The width of the plates is defined according to the specifications of the supplier where they are manufactured. The length of the plates, rounded up to the next 10 cm increment for ease of manufacture, is calculated by:</paragraph>
        <target refid="equation-plate-length-calc"></target>
        <math_block docname="Sedimentation/Sed_Plates" ids="equation-plate-length-calc" label="plate_length_calc" nowrap="False" number="1" xml:space="preserve">  L_{Placa}=\frac{S_{Placa}\left(\frac{V_{Sed}}{V_{Captura}}-1\right)+T_{Placa}\frac{V_{Sed}}{V_{Captura}}}{\sin{\alpha_{Placa}}\cos{\alpha_{Placa}}}</math_block>
        <line_block>
            <line>Where</line>
            <line><math>S_{Plate}</math> = the separation between the plates = <problematic ids="id3" refid="id2">|S.SedPlate|</problematic></line>
            <line><math>V_{Sed}</math> = the upward velocity in the settler = <problematic ids="id5" refid="id4">|V.SedUpBod|</problematic></line>
            <line><math>V_{Capture}</math> = the capture rate = <problematic ids="id7" refid="id6">|V.SedCBod|</problematic></line>
            <line><math>T_{Plate}</math> = the thickness of the plates = <problematic ids="id9" refid="id8">|T.SedPlate|</problematic></line>
            <line><math>\alpha_{Plate}</math> = the angle of inclination of the plates = <problematic ids="id11" refid="id10">|AN.SedPlate|</problematic></line>
        </line_block>
        <paragraph>The number of plates per tank is calculated according to the active length of the tank:</paragraph>
        <target refid="equation-number-of-plates-per-tank"></target>
        <math_block docname="Sedimentation/Sed_Plates" ids="equation-number-of-plates-per-tank" label="number_of_plates_per_tank" nowrap="False" number="2" xml:space="preserve">  N_{Placas}=\frac{L_{SedActivo}\sin{\alpha_{Placa}}-T_{Placa}}{S_{Placa}+T_{Placa}}</math_block>
        <line_block>
            <line>Where</line>
            <line><math>L_{SedActive}</math> = the active length of the settler = <problematic ids="id13" refid="id12">|L.SedActiveEst|</problematic></line>
        </line_block>
        <paragraph>The number of plates per module is defined by the total number of plates per tank so that there is a whole number of modules per tank, with a minimum number of 8 plates per module.</paragraph>
